It's the judge's job to care that the law is faithfully enforced.  This
protects all of us.  It's not the judge's job to slake your need for
vengeance as quickly as possible.  In any case, it seems to me that your
outrage is misdirected:  why aren't you angry at the prison officials who
failed to follow the law?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I don't call that justice.
">

If there were justice, then the state could revive the victim.  But as
you pointed out, the victim remains dead.  He can never receive justice,
and is past caring.  What you mean is that the state didn't extract
retribution quickly enough for you.

Too bad.  The rest of us are safer when judges require that prison
officials follow the law.  If that requires that you wait a few months to
see the state kill a convict, I think that's a fair trade.

