Damn it Larry!  We're agreeing far too often! :)
I'm *technically* pro-death penalty.  The only reason I'm not
*really* pro is because innocent people do get convicted of crimes.
And there is no way to undo a death sentence, once carried out, if it
is later found that the convicted was innocent.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Besides, it would be a delay for pending death row cases, not a
&gt;commutation of sentences.
">

There's always a *possibility* of the sentence being commuted,
until the final appeal is done.  Even if by some strange quirk of fate
this should happen in Robinson's case, it doesn't mean justice hasn't
been done, as Bill has implied.

